## System Spec Dispute Inference

When a negotiation fails at the specs stage, the system attempts to infer *which* specs were the source of disagreement — without relying solely on what the user reports.

### How `inferSpecsDisputes()` works

```typescript
// Pseudocode — src/lib/failureTracking.ts
function inferSpecsDisputes(inquiry: InquiryWithRelations): InferredDispute[] {
  const results: Map<string, InferredDispute> = new Map();

  for (const clarification of inquiry.clarifications) {
    for (const question of clarification.questions) {
      for (const spec of inquiry.specNegotiations) {
        // Case-insensitive match between clarification question text and spec label
        if (question.toLowerCase().includes(spec.specLabel.toLowerCase())) {
          const existing = results.get(spec.specKey) ?? {
            specKey: spec.specKey,
            confidence: 0,
            evidence: []
          };
          existing.confidence = Math.min(existing.confidence + 0.2, 1.0); // cap at 1.0
          existing.evidence.push(question);
          results.set(spec.specKey, existing);
        }
      }
    }
  }

  return [...results.values()].sort((a, b) => b.confidence - a.confidence);
}
```

Each time a clarification question text matches a spec label, confidence for that spec increases by 0.2, capped at 1.0. A spec with 5+ matching clarification questions reaches maximum confidence.

The output is an ordered list of `{ specKey, confidence: 0–1, evidence: string[] }` representing the system's assessment of which specs drove the failure.

