## F1 Score Calculation

The system-inferred dispute list and the user-reported dispute list are compared using precision, recall, and F1 score. This measures how well the system's inference matches what the withdrawing party actually cited.

### `compareSpecsDisputes()` — full logic

```typescript
function compareSpecsDisputes(
  systemInferred: InferredDispute[],    // from inferSpecsDisputes()
  userReported: string[]                // specKeys from withdrawal form
): ComparisonResult {
  const systemKeys = new Set(systemInferred.map(d => d.specKey));
  const userKeys   = new Set(userReported);

  const truePositives  = [...systemKeys].filter(k => userKeys.has(k)).length;
  const falsePositives = [...systemKeys].filter(k => !userKeys.has(k)).length;
  const falseNegatives = [...userKeys].filter(k => !systemKeys.has(k)).length;

  const precision = truePositives / (truePositives + falsePositives) || 0;
  const recall    = truePositives / (truePositives + falseNegatives) || 0;
  const f1Score   = (precision + recall > 0)
    ? 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
    : 0;

  return {
    systemOnly:  [...systemKeys].filter(k => !userKeys.has(k)),
    userOnly:    [...userKeys].filter(k => !systemKeys.has(k)),
    agreement:   [...systemKeys].filter(k =>  userKeys.has(k)),
    precision,
    recall,
    f1Score
  };
}
```

The result is stored in `SpecsFailureDetail.comparison` as JSON:

```json
{
  "systemOnly":  ["packagingType"],
  "userOnly":    ["colorSpec"],
  "agreement":   ["tensileStrength", "moistureContent"],
  "precision":   0.67,
  "recall":      0.5,
  "f1Score":     0.57
}
```

Over time, the aggregate F1 score distribution tells us how well the clarification-based inference model predicts actual spec disputes — and where it systematically misses.

